  as concrete submodules);
* `L i : FDRep k (GL_N k)` whose carrier is
  `Ôćą(S i) ÔćĺÔéŚ[symGroupImage k V n] V^ÔŐŚn`, with the `GL_N`-action given by
  post-composition with `g ÔćŽ g^{ÔŐŚn}` (which lies in
  `centralizer(symGroupImage)` by the centralizer identity);
* a `k`-linear iso `L_carrier i : (L i : Type u) ÔëâÔéŚ[k]
  (Ôćą(S i) ÔćĺÔéŚ[symGroupImage k V n] V^ÔŐŚn)` identifying the bundled FDRep
  carrier with the explicit hom-space (it is `LinearEquiv.refl` after
  the `FGModuleCat.of_carrier` defeq);
* explicit iso `e : V^ÔŐŚn ÔëâÔéŚ[k] ÔĘüßÁó Ôćą(S i) ÔŐŚ[k] (L i : Type u)` whose
  inverse on pure tensors is the evaluation map:
  `e.symm (of i (v ÔŐŚÔéť l)) = (L_carrier i l) v`;
* the `GL_N`-action on each `L i` is, after the `L_carrier` identification,
  post-composition by `g ÔćŽ g^{ÔŐŚn}`:
  `(L_carrier i ((L i).¤ü g l)) v =
   PiTensorProduct.map (fun _ ÔćŽ mulVecLin g.val) ((L_carrier i l) v)`.

The `L_carrier` clause sidesteps a defeq fragility: when stating the
existential, `(L i : Type u)` is universally quantified and not yet
concretised, so an `l : (L i : Type u)` cannot be applied to `v` as a
linear map without the explicit identification with `Ôćą(S i) ÔćĺÔéŚ[A] E`.

This is the form required by the `GL_N`-equivariance argument
(`glTensorRep_equivariant_schurWeyl_decomposition`,
issue #2540): the evaluation formula together with the post-composition
`GL_N`-action formula make equivariance computable on pure tensors. -/
